Diagnosis.
The new species if assigned to the genus 

Phrynopus
sensu Hedges et al. (
2008
)

because its general appearance matches with other species placed in this genus, and these are the only known terraranas occurring in high altitude grasslands of the Cordillera Oriental in central 
Peru
. 

Phrynopus chaparroi

is a medium sized species of 

Phrynopus

having the following combination of characters: (
1
) skin on dorsum coarsely tuberculate with a mass of protuberant subconical tubercles in the postympanic area, skin on venter, throat and ventral surfaces of thighs areolate; discoidal fold absent, thoracic fold absent; dorsolateral fold absent; (
2
) tympanic membrane and tympanic annulus not observable through the skin; (
3
) snout rounded in dorsal and lateral views; (
4
) upper eyelid with irregular small tubercles, narrower than IOD; cranial crests absent; (
5
) dentigerous processes of vomers absent; (
6
) vocal slits absent, nuptial pad present (

